---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "SPYD Dividend Analysis & History",
  description: "Are you paying too much to own high-yield S&P 500 stocks? We examine the latest fees, yield numbers, and payout history so you can keep more of your returns.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "SPYD Dividend Analysis & History",
      "description": meta.description,
      "datePublished": meta.published,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the SPYD expense ratio in 2024?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The SPYD expense ratio is notably low, currently set at 0.07% annually. This means you pay just $7 per year for every $10,000 invested, making it a highly cost-effective option for dividend investors."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the current dividend yield for SPYD?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "SPYD currently offers a dividend yield of approximately 4.08%, though this can fluctuate based on the share prices and payouts of its underlying holdings."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How often does SPYD pay dividends?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "SPYD distributes dividends on a quarterly schedule, typically in March, June, September, and December."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is the SPYD expense ratio worth it for the yield?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, given its low 0.07% cost, the expense ratio takes only a minuscule fraction of the ~4.08% yield, allowing investors to keep the vast majority of their income."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How are stocks selected for the SPYD ETF?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "SPYD tracks the S&P 500 High Dividend Index, which consists of the top 80 highest dividend-yielding companies within the broader S&P 500, equally weighted."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/spyd-expense-ratio-2024" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content container">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>SPYD Dividend Analysis & History</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Deep dive into the SPDR Portfolio S&P 500 High Dividend ETF, its payouts, and the true cost of ownership.</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Yield and Payout Breakdown</h2>
      <p>When searching for "spyd expense ratio 2024" or general "spyd expense ratio" metrics, investors are fundamentally asking: <em>am I keeping enough of my yield?</em> The SPDR Portfolio S&P 500 High Dividend ETF (SPYD) is designed to provide high levels of income and capital appreciation by tracking the top 80 dividend-yielding stocks in the S&P 500.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Key Metrics</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Current Dividend Yield:</strong> ~4.08%</li>
          <li><strong>Expense Ratio:</strong> 0.07%</li>
          <li><strong>Payout Frequency:</strong> Quarterly</li>
          <li><strong>Assets Under Management (AUM):</strong> ~$7.54 Billion</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p>With an expense ratio of just 0.07%, the management fee is virtually negligible compared to the ~4.08% yield. This translates to a cost of only $7 annually per $10,000 invested.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>5-Year Dividend History</h2>
      <p>Because SPYD is an ETF composed of 80 different stocks, its dividend payouts can vary quarter to quarter based on the specific dividend declarations of its underlying holdings.</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Ex-Dividend Date</th>
            <th>Amount ($)</th>
            <th>Frequency</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Dec 22, 2025</td>
            <td>0.549</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Sep 22, 2025</td>
            <td>0.489</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Jun 23, 2025</td>
            <td>0.500</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Mar 24, 2025</td>
            <td>0.419</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Dec 20, 2024</td>
            <td>0.547</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><em>*Data points include recent and projected distributions based on historical pacing. SPYD's payments tend to peak in December when many underlying companies pay special dividends or true-up their annual targets.</em></p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Dividend Growth and Sector Breakdown</h2>
      <p>SPYD provides equal weighting to its 80 holdings, which naturally skews the ETF toward traditionally high-yield sectors. As of recent filings, the fund has significant exposure to Financials, Real Estate, and Utilities. This sector tilt means SPYD is heavily influenced by interest rate environments—higher rates can pressure Real Estate and Utilities, while potentially benefiting Financials.</p>
      <p>While the yield is high, the <em>growth rate</em> of that dividend is often slower than a pure dividend growth fund (like SCHD) because companies with the highest current yields are often mature, slower-growing businesses.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Comparison to Category Averages</h2>
      <p>Compared to the broad S&P 500 (which yields just over 1%, see our <a href="/ishares-core-sp-500-etf-ivv-expense-ratio">IVV Analysis</a>), SPYD offers nearly quadruple the income. When evaluated against other high-yield dividend ETFs, SPYD's 0.07% expense ratio makes it one of the most cost-effective tools available for passive income generation. Some specialized income funds (such as covered call ETFs like those analyzed in our <a href="/high-yield-dividend-etf-passive-income">HIGH ETF review</a>) may offer higher yields but come with significantly higher fees.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Interactive Dividend Reinvestment Calculator</h2>
      <p>Calculate your projected income minus the expense ratio drag using current metrics.</p>

      <div class="card" id="calcContainer" data-initialized="false">
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="shares" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Shares Owned:</label>
          <input type="number" id="shares" value="500" min="1" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="sharePrice" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Share Price ($):</label>
          <input type="number" id="sharePrice" value="38.50" step="0.01" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="yield" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Dividend Yield (%):</label>
          <input type="number" id="yield" value="4.08" step="0.01" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="expRatio" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Expense Ratio (%):</label>
          <input type="number" id="expRatio" value="0.07" step="0.01" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Gross Annual Income: <span id="grossIncome" style="color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.1rem;">$785.40</span></h4>
          <h4 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Annual Expense Fee: <span id="feeAmount" style="color: #e74c3c; font-size: 1.1rem;">-$13.48</span></h4>
          <h4 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Net Annual Income: <span id="netIncome" style="color: var(--accent-color); font-size: 1.25rem;">$771.93</span></h4>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the SPYD expense ratio in 2024?</summary>
        <p>The SPYD expense ratio is notably low, currently set at 0.07% annually. This means you pay just $7 per year for every $10,000 invested, making it a highly cost-effective option for dividend investors.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the current dividend yield for SPYD?</summary>
        <p>SPYD currently offers a dividend yield of approximately 4.08%, though this can fluctuate based on the share prices and payouts of its underlying holdings.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How often does SPYD pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>SPYD distributes dividends on a quarterly schedule, typically in March, June, September, and December.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is the SPYD expense ratio worth it for the yield?</summary>
        <p>Yes, given its low 0.07% cost, the expense ratio takes only a minuscule fraction of the ~4.08% yield, allowing investors to keep the vast majority of their income.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How are stocks selected for the SPYD ETF?</summary>
        <p>SPYD tracks the S&P 500 High Dividend Index, which consists of the top 80 highest dividend-yielding companies within the broader S&P 500, equally weighted.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    function initSpydCalculator() {
      const container = document.getElementById('calcContainer');
      if (!container || container.dataset.initialized === 'true') return;

      const sharesInput = document.getElementById('shares');
      const priceInput = document.getElementById('sharePrice');
      const yieldInput = document.getElementById('yield');
      const expInput = document.getElementById('expRatio');

      const grossOutput = document.getElementById('grossIncome');
      const feeOutput = document.getElementById('feeAmount');
      const netOutput = document.getElementById('netIncome');

      if (!sharesInput || !priceInput || !yieldInput || !expInput || !grossOutput || !feeOutput || !netOutput) return;

      function updateCalc() {
        const shares = parseFloat(sharesInput.value) || 0;
        const price = parseFloat(priceInput.value) || 0;
        const yieldPct = parseFloat(yieldInput.value) || 0;
        const expPct = parseFloat(expInput.value) || 0;

        const totalValue = shares * price;
        const grossIncome = totalValue * (yieldPct / 100);
        const fees = totalValue * (expPct / 100);
        const netIncome = grossIncome - fees;

        grossOutput.textContent = '$' + grossIncome.toFixed(2);
        feeOutput.textContent = '-$' + fees.toFixed(2);
        netOutput.textContent = '$' + netIncome.toFixed(2);
      }

      sharesInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);
      priceInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);
      yieldInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);
      expInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);

      container.dataset.initialized = 'true';
    }

    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initSpydCalculator);
    document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initSpydCalculator);
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    th, td { padding: 0.75rem 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.85rem; text-transform: uppercase; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
